Ask HN: Morning “standup”, minus the bad parts, for morning motivation?
text:
Curious if anyone has had similar thoughts, or would be interested in my proposed scheme:

Cause: I’d like to get up earlier. I’m a young freelancer. I can do it. It’s just _hard_ when I can lay in bed and no one will be disappointed in me, since my first meeting is probably 1pm. This leads to wasted billable hours hitting the snooze button, and general quality-of-life hits.

What I’d really like is a small group of tech people who expect eachother to show up at a meeting-like thing, fairly early in the morning, at the same time every day. Not really to talk about work, just… whatever.

Call it networking, but early in the morning. And hard-capped at 5-10min, max. No exceptions, this is a way to start the day consistently, not a social group.

Curious if anyone’s tried something like this with people from outside your company.

title: Ask HN: What do you use for basic data analysis, visualization, and graphing?
text:
I often find myself with some JSON data that I want to visualize. I usually end up converting to CSV, uploading to a Google Sheet, and manually creating charts. BUT this is really time consuming and I find Google Sheets charts pretty difficult and painful for quickly exploring different views of the original data.

So what do you use for this type of thing?

I know python has lots of good utils for data wrangling & graphing, but I'd prefer a solution which is: no-code, gives me a bunch of common graph views I can quickly choose between, and that "just works" 99% of the time.

Thanks!
